# HISTORY: this was a RUNTIME test. A HashMap destroyed through a &poke parameter has
# capacity 0 and null buckets; insert() then probed off the null bucket pointer and
# SEGFAULTED. Tier 4.2 bounded the probe by capacity so it traps (RE2022) instead of
# segfaulting, and this test pinned that trap.
#
# The trap was containment for a CHECKER hole (#168): the borrow checker only marked a
# variable destroyed on a literal `m.destroy()` in the same function, so it never saw
# this one and CE2406 never fired. #168 is now FIXED -- a destroy-effect summary
# propagates the callee's effect to the call site -- so this program no longer compiles
# and can never reach the trap. The test now asserts the diagnostic that supersedes it.
#
# The RE2022 trap REMAINS as defense-in-depth: the summary deliberately
# under-approximates (it cannot see a generic callee, an extension method destroying its
# implicit `self`, a library callee, or an argument that is not a bare name -- e.g.
# `wreck(&poke h.m)`). Its direct test coverage is gone with this conversion, which is a
# real cost, accepted: a reachable trap with a test was traded for an unreachable trap
# behind a compile error.
# EXPECT_ERROR_CODE: CE2406
use <collections/hashmap>

fn wreck(&poke HashMap@(string, i32) m) ~:
    m.destroy()
    return Result.Ok(~)

fn main() i32:
    let HashMap@(string, i32) map = HashMap.new()
    map.insert("a", 1)
    wreck(&poke map)
    map.insert("b", 2)
    return Result.Ok(0)
